Section 3.3.1

1.

The points are not blue in the plot because aesthetics are mapped to variables in the data set when you include them in the aes() function. If you want to force a certain aesthic, you have to specify this outside of the aes() function.

2.

mpg

By looking at the help file we can read the descriptions of each variable, but we can also see, at the top of each column when we print out the data set above, what type each column is.

Categorical variables are: manufacturer; model; cyl; trans; drv; fl; and class. Continuous variables are: displ; year; city; and hwy. Note that we could also interpret some variables that R has formatted as integers as ordinal variables, such as year.

3.

ggplot(data = mpg) +

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, size = cty))

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = trans))

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, size = trans))
## Warning: Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, shape = trans))
## Warning: The shape palette can deal with a maximum of 6 discrete values
## because more than 6 becomes difficult to discriminate; you have
## 10. Consider specifying shapes manually if you must have them.
## Warning: Removed 96 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

For color, categorical variables are given discrete colors corresponding to categories, and the color palette does not have an order. Continuous variables have a gradient-style sequential color palette.

For size, categorical variables are given discrete sizes corresponding to categories, and it looks like the sizes correlate with the categories in alphabetical order. Continuous variables are binned in an automatic way and given sizes that correspond to the direction of the variable, e.g.getting bigger as the variable gets bigger.

For shape, a limited number of categories are given their own shapes. You cannot use the shape aesthetic with continuous variables.

4.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = cty, size = cty))

When you map multiple aesthetics to the same variable, all aesthetics are plotted simultaneously and a legend is given for each one.

5.

From the help file for geom_point() there is an example at the bottom that describes that the stroke aesthetic can control the width of the border around the plotting points.

From the cheatsheet it looks like the stroke aesthetic only works for geom_point() and geom_count().

6.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = displ < 5))

Doing this seems to plot the results of the expression. So, for each observation, if displ < 5, then the point is given the category of TRUE, otherwise it is given the category of FALSE, and then the TRUE and FALSE categories are mapped to colors.

Section 3.5.1: #4 and #5 only

4.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ class, nrow = 2)

The faceting can help reveal patterns which exist when broken down by categories. These patterns would otherwise be masked by the overlapping of points. For example, 2-seaters and compact cars are clumped together in a certain region of space corresponding to their engine size and gas mileage. This can sometimes be more useful than colors if there is a lot more data with overlapping points. On the other hand, we will not be able to observe any global relationships that may exist, but this is easily remedied by looking at a simple scatterplot.

5.

The nrow and ncol arguments describe how many rows and columns, respectively, the panels will be placed in. The as.table and dir arguments can also help you control the layout. facet_grid doesnt use these arguments because you have to define your row and column facetting variables explicitly.

  )

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_smooth(
    mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv)

## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

show.legend = FALSE removes the legend for the geom_smooth(). It was used in the earlier example in this chapter to make comparing the three plots easier.

4.

The se argument to geom_smooth() creates and displays confidence intervals around the smoothed line.

5.

These two graphs should not look any different. In the first set of code the two geoms will use the same mapping that is defined in the ggplot() function. Its a useful way to write less code.
